  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws are designed to prevent the illegal process of concealing the origins of money obtained through illicit activities, thereby making it appear legitimate. Here are some key international instruments and organizations involved in the fight against money laundering:\n\n1. **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This is one of the earliest international agreements targeting money laundering, particularly in relation to drug trafficking.\n\n2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: Established in 1989 by the G7, the FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Its recommendations are widely recognized as the global standard in anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) efforts.\n\n3. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, this treaty includes provisions to combat money laundering.\n\n4. **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention addresses various forms of corruption and includes measures to prevent and combat money laundering.\n\n5. **European Union Directives**: The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) that require member states to enact legislation to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing within their jurisdictions. The most recent directive as of 2020 was the 6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD).\n\n6. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**: While not a law-making body, the Basel Committee issues guidelines and recommendations for banks to manage risks, including those related to money laundering.\n\n7. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**: These institutions provide technical assistance and conduct assessments of countries' AML and CFT frameworks.\n\nCountries around the world have enacted domestic laws to implement these international standards. These laws typically include requirements for financial institutions and other regulated entities to conduct due diligence on their customers, report suspicious activities, and maintain records of transactions.\n\nIt's important to note that while these international frameworks exist, enforcement and effectiveness can vary significantly from one country to another. Nations are expected to enact their own legislation in line with these international standards and to cooperate with each other in the fight against money laundering.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
